Explanation:

We use a StringBuilder object (sb) to efficiently build the merged string. We iterate through both strings simultaneously using two pointers, i and j, starting from their first characters. We compare the characters at positions i and j. If the character at position i in word1 is greater than the character at position j in word2, we append the characters from both strings. If the character at position i in word1 is less than the character at position j in word2, we append the characters from word2 and word1. If they are equal, we append both characters from word1 and word2. After appending, we increment both pointers i and j. This process continues until either string becomes empty.

The time complexity is O(min(m, n), where m and n are the lengths of word1 and word2 respectively, because we compare characters at most m positions and append characters at most n positions. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a StringBuilder object. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs simple comparisons and string operations, which have low energy consumption.

